\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Assignment 5 Problem Two
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Michael Cai
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph*
2.
 In this problem, we explore whether for any continuous functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
int_{-
\backslash
infty}^
\backslash
infty f(x)dx = 
\backslash
lim_{b
\backslash
to
\backslash
infty} 
\backslash
int_{-b}^{b} f(x)dx$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
(a) Find 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{\infty}\frac{2x}{x^{2}+1}dx$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{\infty}\frac{2x}{x^{2}+1}dx=\lim_{b\to\infty}\int_{0}^{b}\frac{2x}{x^{2}+1}dx$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we use u-substitution and let 
\begin_inset Formula $u=x^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $du=2xdx$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This changes the upper limit to be equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 and the lower limit equals 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{b\to\infty}\int_{0}^{b}\frac{2x}{x^{2}+1}dx=\lim_{b\to\infty}\int_{1}^{b^{2}+1}\frac{du}{u}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=ln|u|\bigg|_{1}^{b^{2}+1}=ln|b^{2}+1|-ln|1|=ln|b^{2}+1|$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

, which thus equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
(b) Using your solution to part (b), determine whether 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{2x}{x^{2}+1}dx$
\end_inset

 is convergent or divergent.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve an integral which has the bounds 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

, each of the separate components of the integral when split into the pieces
 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-\infty}^{0}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

must be separately convergent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because we have already checked 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 and found it to be divergent, then we can conclude that the two-sided 
\begin_inset Formula $[-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 integral must also be divergent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
(c) Find 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{b\to\infty}\int_{-b}^{b}\frac{2x}{x^{2}+1}dx$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have already solved for the portion, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{b\to\infty}\int_{0}^{b}\frac{2x}{x^{2}+1}dx$
\end_inset

, so now we just need to solve for the portion from the bound 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

 to 0.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{b\to-\infty}\int_{b}^{0}\frac{2x}{x^{2}+1}dx$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the same u-substitution as we used in the previous problem, we get
 the answer:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=ln|u|\bigg|_{b^{2}+1}^{1}=ln|1|-ln|b^{2}+1|=-ln|b^{2}+1|$
\end_inset

 as b approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty,$
\end_inset

 which thus equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{b\to\infty}\int_{-b}^{b}\frac{2x}{x^{2}+1}dx=\infty-\infty$
\end_inset

, which is still divergent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
(d) State your conclusion.
 Is it true that for all continuous functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
int_{-
\backslash
infty}^
\backslash
infty f(x)dx = 
\backslash
lim_{b
\backslash
to
\backslash
infty} 
\backslash
int_{-b}^{b} f(x)dx?$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Yes, this statement is true for all continuous functions because of the
 definition of a limit.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the limit, which is the approximation of a finite number, b, as it approaches
 an infinite value, 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty,$
\end_inset

 exists then the improper integral is convergent, but if the limit does
 not exist as a finite number then the improper integral is divergent.
\end_layout

